ce:section.ce:para:
Bimetallic dual emissive NCs was synthesized according to the manner reported in our previous work (Babaee et al., 2019) by a small change in Au and Ag precursors ratio (Scheme 1
                        ). Our results in this study and our previous work are in agreement with other reports that show the synergetic effect of Au and Ag atoms in bimetallic NCs not only increase the stability (Maretti et al., 2009) but also, enhance the fluorescence emission intensity (Dou et al., 2014; Kobayashi et al., 2014). As the first characterizations, the UV–Vis absorption spectrum and, fluorescence excitation and emission spectra of the as-synthesized Ins(Au/Ag)NCs were done and shown in Fig. 1
                        A. The absence of the surface Plasmon resonance for Ag and Au nanoparticles in this region demonstrated that the Ins(Au/Ag)NCs were synthesized with no larger particles (Bi et al., 2012). The as-synthesized NCs solution with a pale yellow color show the main excitation band at about 330 nm, and dual emissive blue and red fluorescence emission centered at about 410 and 630 nm respectively (Fig. 1A). As proved in our previous work, the red emission fluorescence centered at around 630 nm is associated with the formation of bimetallic NCs which also certified by TEM image (Fig. 1B), and XPS data (Fig. 1C and D).
